I've created a hybrid version that combines the best features from all three implementations plus adds synonym learning! Here's what makes it powerful:
ðŸš€ Key Features
1. Multi-Stage Pipeline (4 Stages)

Stage 1: Exact matching (fastest)
Stage 2: Phonetic matching (Soundex + Metaphone) - handles misspellings
Stage 3: Multi-metric fuzzy matching (Fuzzy + Jaccard + N-gram + Levenshtein + Jaro-Winkler)
Stage 4: TF-IDF with character n-grams (handles partial words)

2. Synonym Learning ðŸ§ 

Tracks successful mappings automatically
Identifies patterns (e.g., "cardio" â†’ Cardiology)
Exports learned abbreviations for reuse
Minimum frequency threshold prevents noise

3. Compound Specialty Handling

Splits on /, ,, +, &, and
Maps each segment independently
Combines results intelligently

4. Robust Normalization

Handles Unicode, diacritics
Expands abbreviations
Removes noise words
Case-insensitive
With Custom Synonyms

python standardize_hybrid.py \
  --nucc nucc_taxonomy_master.csv \
  --input input.csv \
  --out output.csv \
  --synonyms my_synonyms.csv \
  --threshold 0.70

With Synonym Learning (Recommended!)
python standardize_hybrid.py \
  --nucc nucc_taxonomy_master.csv \
  --input input.csv \
  --out output.csv \
  --learn-synonyms \
  --save-learned learned_synonyms.csv
After the first run, use the learned synonyms:

python standardize_hybrid.py \
  --nucc nucc_taxonomy_master.csv \
  --input new_input.csv \
  --out new_output.csv \
  --synonyms learned_synonyms.csv


python standardize_hybrid.py \
  --nucc nucc_taxonomy_master.csv \
  --input input.csv \
  --out output.csv \
  --synonyms custom_synonyms.csv \
  --threshold 0.65 \
  --topn 5 \
  --learn-synonyms \
  --save-learned learned_synonyms.csv




